diography in Pediatric and Congenital Heart Disease from Fetus to the Adult, Second edition 2016.","guid":"0bht5HMhGjU4bElqrCfIvA","children":[]},{"id":"311","parent":"297","text":"14. Lupo PJ, et al. Epidemiology of Ebstein Anomaly: Prevalence and Patterns in Texas, 1999-2005. American Journal of Medical Genetics Part A. 2011;155A(5):1007-14.","guid":"hpNAds-9a1lcf1HxjrlFBQ","children":[]},{"id":"312","parent":"297","text":"15. Martin de Miguel I, et al. Prognostic Implications of Atrial Fibrillation in Adults With Ebstein Anomaly. Heart. 2023;109(6):442-448.","guid":"zvLG0oti8QlOMdFkmvtfYg","children":[]},{"id":"313","parent":"297","text":"16. Nichols DG et al. Critical heart disease in infants and children, 2006.","guid":"Gu0wVJKB6N3yUNLLaQYFZA","children":[]},{"id":"314","parent":"297","text":"17. Page RL, et al. 2015 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline for the Management of Adult Patients With Supraventricular Tachycardia. Heart Rhythm. 2016;13(4):e136-221.","guid":"AQlho1nTNXnhoG3GNknduQ","children":[]},{"id":"315","parent":"297","text":"18. Ports TA, Silverman NH, Schiller NB. Two-Dimensional Echocardiographic Assessment of Ebstein's Anomaly. Circulation. 1978;58(2):336-43.","guid":"MgKH_c8XPMyThJRZrjGyTw","children":[]},{"id":"316","parent":"297","text":"19. Puchalski MD, et al. Guidelines for Performing a Comprehensive Transesophageal Echocardiographic Examination in Children\\Nand All Patients With Congenital Heart Disease. Journal of the American Society of Echocardiography. 2019;32(2):173-215.","guid":"l53V7xFZYPGJhcDYLZRMNA","children":[]},{"id":"317","parent":"297","text":"20. Sedaghat-Hamedani F, Andelfinger GU, Meder B. Human Genetics of Ebstein's Anomaly. Advances in Experimental Medicine and Biology. 2024;1441:909-914.","guid":"K8VBWtkyqqeyfA-_85mO3A","children":[]},{"id":"318","parent":"297","text":"21. Sicko RJ, et al. Genetic Variants in Isolated Ebstein Anomaly Implicated in Myocardial Development Pathways. PLoS One. 2016;11(10):e0165174.","guid":"t9vm9_fVCBiySsoL-pC9xg","children":[]},{"id":"319","parent":"297","text":"22. Stout KK, et al. 2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease. Circulation. 2019;139(14):e698-e800.","guid":"2-QtiYiNSwwfEumPZRmxQg","children":[]},{"id":"320","parent":"297","text":"23. Yetman AT, et al. Outcome in Cyanotic Neonates With Ebstein's Anomaly. American Journal of Cardiology. 1998;81(6):749-54.","guid":"wolC5CywzvZ2uhmQkN5sqw","children":[]}]},{"id":"321","parent":"0","text":"Perlas Clínicas","guid":"68E2AFEB66BE4A21868A5396","children":[{"id":"322","parent":"321","text":"DIAGNÓSTICO ECO: desplazamiento apical ≥8 mm/m² del velo septal tricuspídeo — es el criterio diagnóstico definitivo, NO la \"atriealización\" del VD que era el criterio clásico","guid":"FD84128FD6854CE5A93FDCC0","children":[]},{"id":"323","parent":"321","text":"ESPECTRO CLÍNICO: desde diagnóstico fetal (muy severo, alta mortalidad) hasta adultos completamente asintomáticos — la severidad anatómica NO predice siempre el grado funcional","guid":"55FBA506527E42D593B3F881","children":[]},{"id":"324","parent":"321","text":"WPW Y EBSTEIN: el haz accesorio en Ebstein se localiza habitualmente en cara lateral-derecha del anillo tricuspídeo — FA con preexcitación puede generar FV → muerte súbita — mapeo electrofisiológico obligatorio","guid":"B7259D9DF8844E68A94BAC0D","children":[]},{"id":"325","parent":"321","text":"CIANOSIS EN EBSTEIN: por cortocircuito D→I a través de CIA/FOP (presente en 40%) — empeora con aumento de presión en AD y con el ejercicio; puede presentarse en adultos por primera vez","guid":"3AFD166DF0674189BFE227C3","children":[]},{"id":"326","parent":"321","text":"SEMIOLOGÍA: soplo pansistólico en borde esternal izquierdo bajo + desdoblamiento fijo de S2 + ritmo de galope (3°-4° ruido) — \"ruido de tren\" es patognomónico","guid":"99033E00F0F54FB593E2B38D","children":[]},{"id":"327","parent":"321","text":"ÍNDICE DE CELERMAJER: (área AD + VD atrializado) / (área VD funcional + VI + AI) — grado IV (>1.5) asociado a mortalidad perinatal 100%; grado I (<0.5) pronóstico excelente","guid":"773AEFC667E7445B975F09F2","children":[]},{"id":"328","parent":"321","text":"FLUTTER/FA EN SEGUIMIENTO: causa frecuente de descompensación en adultos — amiodarona o ablación si hay síntomas — cardioversión SOLO tras excluir/tratar haz accesorio","guid":"6F86F0F5E5C24E7FAA0737DD","children":[]},{"id":"329","parent":"321","text":"TRASPLANTE CARDÍACO: alternativa a cirugía en Ebstein muy severa con VD no reparable — considerar cuando VD funcional es mínimo y hay IC avanzada refractaria","guid":"951BD5DB6CCD4AE08752B9D8","children":[]},{"id":"330","parent":"321","text":"Referencias","guid":"BC00DDF2A5CD4A608AD86212","children":[{"id":"331","parent":"330","text":"1. Attenhofer Jost CH et al. Ebstein's Anomaly. Circulation. 2007;115(2):277-285.","guid":"089C113286EF42DA9BDC8ABD","children":[]},{"id":"332","parent":"330","text":"2. Celermajer DS et al. Outcome in neonates with Ebstein's anomaly. J Am Coll Cardiol. 1992;19(5):1041-1046.","guid":"69E3BE6FC23149649E86EEC4","children":[]},{"id":"333","parent":"330","text":"3. Correa-Villasenor A et al. Ebstein's malformation of the tricuspid valve. Pediatr Cardiol. 1994;15(4):169-175.","guid":"E6FBE68B20A04543976CA4F5","children":[]},{"id":"334","parent":"330","text":"4. Baumgartner H et al. 2020 ESC Guidelines for Adult Congenital Heart Disease. Eur Heart J. 2021;42(6):563-645.","guid":"36D8C625543B4833B4BB1918","children":[]},{"id":"335","parent":"330","text":"5. Attie F et al. Surgical treatment for Ebstein's anomaly. Clin Cardiol. 1999;22(2):101-106.","guid":"055E713AF1A0453FB044D15E","children":[]}]}]}]},"node_count":335,"relations":[],"cross_references":[],"specialty":"Geriatría","folder":"Entidades clínicas/Ortogeriatría","filename":"Orto Resumen-2026","id":"map_164","resolved_references":[]}